@node Source buffers and sidecars
@section Source buffers and sidecars

A source buffer is the Org document being reviewed.  The default local backend
stores comments in a sibling sidecar whose name ends in @samp{.comments.org}.  For
example, @samp{article.org} uses @samp{article.comments.org}.

Sidecars are ordinary Org files.  Each top-level heading represents a root
comment.  Replies are child headings.  Comment metadata is stored as Org
properties with the @samp{ORG_COMMENTS_} prefix.

@node Anchors
@section Anchors

Inline comments store target text and compact position metadata.  When the
source text changes, @samp{org-comments} can report comments as stale or re-anchor
imported inline comments using exact and fuzzy matching.

@node Page comments
@section Page comments

Page comments are comments about the entire document instead of a specific text
range.  They are represented as footer/page records and can be shown in a page
comments panel.

@node Collaboration state
@section Collaboration state

Backends normalize collaboration metadata into provider-neutral fields:

@itemize
@item
remote identifiers and parent/thread identifiers;
@item
remote state such as present, missing, deleted, or unknown;
@item
local state such as draft, edited, pending push, or push error;
@item
sync state such as clean, dirty, conflict, or error;
@item
resolved and actionable state;
@item
backend-qualified people identity.
@end itemize

See also the backend-neutral model in @samp{../COLLABORATION.md}.

@node Local Org Sidecars
@chapter Local Org Sidecars

The default backend is @samp{org}.  It reads and writes local Org sidecars and does
not require network access.

New sidecar metadata uses only @samp{ORG_COMMENTS_*} properties.  Legacy
@samp{HUB_COMMENT_*} properties are migration input only.  Normal collection reports
legacy sidecars as requiring explicit migration instead of silently reading the
old format.

@node Comment UI
@chapter Comment UI

@samp{org-comments-mode} is the standalone minor mode and the recommended activation
point for users.  It installs Org-native bindings, and when
@samp{org-comments-enable-overlays} is non-nil it also shows overlays for inline
targets and displays page-comment markers.  The default panel is implemented by
@samp{org-comments-panel-mode} and can be replaced or enriched by setting UI adapter
variables.

The package does not install Evil, leader-key, or layout-specific bindings.
Personal keybindings belong in user configuration.

User-facing commands such as @samp{org-comments-open-remote}, @samp{org-comments-push},
@samp{org-comments-reply}, @samp{org-comments-pull}, @samp{org-comments-sync}, and the mark
commands are DWIM: they operate on the current Org source comment when called
from an Org source buffer, and on the current rendered row/source when called
from @samp{org-comments-panel-mode}.

@node Backends
@chapter Backends

Backends register a backend id, capabilities, and operation functions through
@samp{org-comments-register-backend}.  Generic commands detect the active backend
from the current source buffer and dispatch to the backend operation.

Important operations include:

@itemize
@item
list or collect comments;
@item
open the remote comment;
@item
push local comment edits;
@item
pull remote comment state;
@item
sync comments.
@end itemize

Backend @samp{:sync} is comments-only.  It must not perform a full document or page
sync.  Provider packages may offer separate full-document synchronization
commands outside the generic @samp{org-comments} backend contract.

@menu
* Identity resolution::
@end menu

@node Identity resolution
@section Identity resolution

Backends can set @samp{org-comments-resolve-account-id-function} to resolve remote
account IDs into display names for sidecar headings and UI surfaces.  The
callback is called with an account ID and optional directory context, and should
return a display name string or nil.  This keeps provider-specific people stores
outside the generic @samp{org-comments} package.

@node Confluence Backend
@chapter Confluence Backend

The Confluence integration lives in @samp{org-confluence}.  When a source Org buffer
contains @samp{#+CONFLUENCE_PAGE_ID}, the Confluence detector can select the
@samp{confluence} backend for remote comment operations.

The backend supports remote open, push, pull, and comments-only sync.  Full
Confluence page synchronization remains an @samp{org-confluence} responsibility and
is intentionally separate from @samp{org-comments-sync}.

@node Migration
@chapter Migration

Older sidecars may contain @samp{HUB_COMMENT_*} properties.  Run
@samp{org-comments-migrate-sidecar} on one sidecar, or
@samp{org-comments-migrate-directory-sidecars} for a directory of sidecars, to
rewrite those properties to @samp{ORG_COMMENTS_*}.

Migration is explicit by design.  Durable storage should not depend on the
former personal metadata prefix.

